{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bb612f8d-b336-405b-8242-ff08d6b66416","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project and code are fine — the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild nodes resident in memory. The CLI, by default, does not.\n\nHere are three recommendations, in order of impact:\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)\n\n.NET 8+ includes a long-lived MSBuild server that caches the project graph between builds:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nAdd this to your shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`, etc.) to make it permanent.\n\n### 2. Enable MSBuild Node Reuse\n\nThe `dotnet` CLI defaults to `/nodeReuse:false`, killing worker nodes after each build. Override this:\n\n```bash\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\n```\n\nThis keeps worker processes alive between builds, cutting startup overhead.\n\n### 3. Use `dotnet watch` for the Inner Loop\n\nFor rapid edit-build-test cycles, `dotnet watch` keeps the process alive and rebuilds on file changes — no repeated startup cost:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The .csproj doesn't need changes. The overhead is entirely from CLI process lifecycle. Enabling the MSBuild server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) and node reuse (`MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0`) should bring CLI incremental builds close to Visual Studio speed. Use `dotnet watch` for the tightest inner loop.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"21006f3c-38a8-4ed9-91a5-aa7c837e9ef1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is about the difference between how Visual Studio and the CLI handle MSBuild:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** uses an in-process MSBuild server that stays resident in memory. The project graph is already evaluated, so incremental builds just check timestamps and skip quickly.\n\n2. **`dotnet build` from CLI** spawns a new MSBuild process each time, which must:\n   - Start the .NET runtime\n   - Load MSBuild assemblies\n   - Parse and evaluate the project file and all SDK imports\n   - Then check if anything needs rebuilding\n\nThe solution is to enable the **MSBuild build server**, which keeps MSBuild nodes alive between builds to avoid the overhead of process startup and project re-evaluation. This can be controlled via the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable or the `MSBuildServer` property.\n\nThe key recommendations are to set `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`, use `dotnet watch` for file-watching-based incremental rebuilds during development, and ensure node reuse is enabled. By default, `dotnet build` disables node reuse with `/nodeReuse:false`, which kills MSBuild worker nodes after each build—Visual Studio keeps them alive by default. Setting `/nodeReuse:true` or ensuring `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` isn't set to `1` will help maintain those nodes between builds.","outputTokens":1036,"requestId":"1C06:2544DD:13CA5F:1774A1:69E819CF"},"id":"bba313c9-a36b-4869-b264-f5c54444c31a","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:44:22.283Z","parentId":"544f70fa-83fb-4fcd-a9b9-6ddf50f6a50e"}
